<div class="section" id="a1i">
  <div class="act-header">
    <div class="act-num"><div class="act-num-pip">1</div>Activity 1 of 6 · Setup</div>
    <h2 class="act-title">The Rule Switch Game</h2>
    <p class="act-desc">Measures whether your child disengages from an established rule when it changes — or whether old patterns continue to fire automatically. The diagnostic value is in the <em>transition</em> moment, not in correct final sorting.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="setup-box">
    <h3>You will need</h3>
    <div class="setup-items">
      <div class="setup-item"><div class="setup-num">1</div><div class="setup-text"><strong>8 number cards</strong> — write these values: 4, 9, 15, 22, 36, 51, 64, 100</div></div>
      <div class="setup-item"><div class="setup-num">2</div><div class="setup-text">A flat surface with two designated areas — left and right</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="instr-block">
    <h3>Phase 1 — Establish the rule (2 min)</h3>
    <p>Say to your child:</p>
    <div class="script">"Sort these numbers. Multiples of 4 go left, everything else goes right. As fast as you can."</div>
    <p>Let them sort all eight. Multiples of 4 here: 4, 36, 64, 100. Shuffle and repeat twice more. This builds the pattern — it is not yet diagnostic.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="instr-block">
    <h3>Phase 2 — Switch the rule (the diagnostic moment)</h3>
    <p>Immediately after the third sort, without any pause, say:</p>
    <div class="script">"New rule. Square numbers go left, everything else goes right."</div>
    <p>Present the cards again immediately. Square numbers here: 4, 9, 36, 64, 100. <strong>Watch closely. Do not react.</strong> Several cards belong in the same pile as before (4, 36, 64, 100) but for different reasons — does your child re-derive each card or just keep the same placements?</p>
  </div>
  <div class="instr-block">
    <h3>Phase 3 — Introduce an ambiguous-seeming rule</h3>
    <p>Add a new card: <strong>1</strong>. Announce:</p>
    <div class="script">"Last rule: numbers that are both square AND even go left. Everything else goes right."</div>
    <p>Present all nine cards. Watch what your child does with 1 (square but odd — goes right), 9 (square but odd — goes right), and whether they reason explicitly about each or just sort by feel.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="note-box"><strong>Note:</strong> A child who places cards correctly in Phase 3 by actively reasoning ("4 is square and even, so left — 9 is square but odd, so right") is showing something very different from a child who places them correctly by pattern-feel. You are observing the <em>process</em>, not the outcome.</div>
  <div class="btn-row">
    <button class="btn-primary" onclick="goTo('a1o')">I've completed this activity →</button>
  </div>
</div>

