<div class="section" id="a2i">
  <div class="act-header">
    <div class="act-num"><div class="act-num-pip">2</div>Activity 2 of 6 · Setup</div>
    <h2 class="act-title">The Story Maths Game</h2>
    <p class="act-desc">Measures whether your child constructs the full logical structure of a problem before solving, or matches surface language to a known procedure. Read each story at a natural pace. After the last word, wait in silence — you want the first-fire response before self-correction.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="note-box"><strong>Key instruction:</strong> Tell your child to answer as soon as they know — don't wait, don't explain. After you finish reading, say nothing and wait. The first number they say is the most diagnostic data point.</note>
  <div class="story-cards">
    <div class="story-card"><div class="story-card-head"><span class="story-label">Story 1 · Baseline</span><span class="story-ans">Answer: 7</span></div><div class="story-card-body"><div class="story-text">"Mia has 4 apples. She picks 3 more. How many does she have?"</div><div class="story-watch">Baseline only. Speed here reflects confidence, not a cognitive signal.</div></div></div>
    <div class="story-card"><div class="story-card-head"><span class="story-label">Story 2 · Structural reversal ★</span><span class="story-ans">Answer: 4</span></div><div class="story-card-body"><div class="story-text">"A bag had some oranges. I put in 5 more. Now there are 9. How many were in the bag before?"</div><div class="story-watch">The classic reversal. Children who surface-match "put in 5 more" will add and get 14. Children who construct the situation will subtract. Watch especially whether they answer immediately or pause to build the model.</div></div></div>
    <div class="story-card"><div class="story-card-head"><span class="story-label">Story 3 · Hidden comparison</span><span class="story-ans">Answer: 16</span></div><div class="story-card-body"><div class="story-text">"Callum had £24. He spent some money on a book. Now he has £8 less than he started with. How much does he have left?"</div><div class="story-watch">"£8 less than he started with" defines a comparison, not the remainder. Children must retain the starting value (£24) and subtract 8 — not operate on the implicit current amount.</div></div></div>
    <div class="story-card"><div class="story-card-head"><span class="story-label">Story 4 · Ratio language ★★</span><span class="story-ans">Answer: 18</span></div><div class="story-card-body"><div class="story-text">"There are 6 red counters and 3 blue counters. How many red counters would you need to have 3 times as many red as blue?"</div><div class="story-watch">"3 times as many red as blue" requires the child to compute the target (9) and then find the additional amount needed (3). Children who pattern-match "3 times as many" to simple multiplication of 6 will answer 18 for the wrong reasons — or will confuse the question entirely.</div></div></div>
    <div class="story-card"><div class="story-card-head"><span class="story-label">Story 5 · Multi-step with distractor</span><span class="story-ans">Answer: 13</span></div><div class="story-card-body"><div class="story-text">"A class of 20 children goes on a trip. The minibus holds 12. The rest go by car. On the way back, 3 of the car children swap to the minibus. How many children are now in the car?"</div><div class="story-watch">Requires constructing the intermediate state (8 in the car) before applying the final change. Watch whether your child holds the intermediate value or tries to work end-to-end in one step.</div></div></div>
    <div class="story-card"><div class="story-card-head"><span class="story-label">Story 6 · Abstract relationship ★★★ Highest signal</span><span class="story-ans">Answer: 5</span></div><div class="story-card-body"><div class="story-text">"Amy has twice as many stickers as Ben. Together they have 15. How many does Ben have?"</div><div class="story-watch">Requires simultaneous constraint satisfaction — holding two relationships at once. Children who try arithmetic without a structural model will guess. Children who construct the model (Amy = 2×Ben; Amy+Ben = 15) will solve correctly. This is the most diagnostic story at this level.</div></div></div>
  </div>
