    <p class="act-desc">The most revealing activity. Separates answers that were retrieved from answers that were genuinely understood — and, at this level, probes whether your child can reason across categories and spot structural analogies.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="instr-block">
    <h3>The setup</h3>
    <p>Choose problems your child can already solve correctly. After each correct answer, say:</p>
    <div class="script">"That's right — but can you tell me WHY that's the answer? Teach it to me like I'm a robot who doesn't know anything."</div>
    <p>The "robot" framing removes the social awkwardness of explaining something "simple." Run all three probes.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="phase-cards">
    <div class="phase-card">
      <div class="phase-card-head"><div class="phase-icon" style="background:var(--steel)">1</div><div class="phase-card-title">Probe 1 — Why does multiplication work? "What is 6 × 4?"</div></div>
      <div class="phase-card-body">When they say 24, ask: "Why is it 24? What is multiplication actually doing?" Listen for retrieval ("because that's the answer") versus rule-labelling ("because you times them") versus genuine explanation ("6 groups of 4 things each — if you count all of them you get 24"). The third response shows the model, not the result.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="phase-card">
      <div class="phase-card-head"><div class="phase-icon" style="background:var(--amber)">2</div><div class="phase-card-title">Probe 2 — Proportional reasoning: "If 3 pencils cost 90p, how much does 1 pencil cost?"</div></div>
      <div class="phase-card-body">When they say 30p, ask: "Why? How did you know to divide?" Listen for whether they justify the division (because you need to find one part of the total, and there are 3 equal parts) or just name the operation ("because you divide 90 by 3").</div>
    </div>
    <div class="phase-card">
      <div class="phase-card-head"><div class="phase-icon" style="background:var(--green)">3</div><div class="phase-card-title">Probe 3 — Structural analogy: "Is 'hot' to 'cold' the same kind of relationship as 'fast' to 'slow'?"</div></div>
      <div class="phase-card-body">Either answer is fine. Ask "Why?" This probes whether your child can articulate the structure of a relationship (opposites on a scale) or just assert similarity/difference. Then ask: "Can you think of another pair that works the same way?" A child who gives a novel pair has extracted the underlying structure, not just memorised the example.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
